00:26.226 --> 00:30.026
[Crickets chirp, owl hoots]

00:33.133 --> 00:37.900
[Drums beating]

00:37.971 --> 00:42.499
[Chanting]

00:56.589 --> 01:00.787
[Drumming and chanting
continue]

01:07.734 --> 01:09.065
[Wind whistling]

01:23.216 --> 01:24.808
[Wind whistling]

01:24.884 --> 01:28.547
[Drumming and chanting
continue]

01:39.065 --> 01:41.465
[Wind whistling]

01:41.534 --> 01:44.935
[Drumming and chanting stop]

01:46.005 --> 01:50.008
[Shouts
in native language]

02:02.489 --> 02:04.650
[Metal rattling]

02:10.562 --> 02:13.031
"Safety first"...
that's my motto.

02:13.099 --> 02:15.499
When one is doing
dangerous work,

02:15.568 --> 02:19.504
one must pay careful attention
to the safety of one's body,

02:19.572 --> 02:21.005
know what I mean?

02:21.074 --> 02:22.507
Aah.

02:22.575 --> 02:25.840
But one day,
I'll be a camp counselor,

02:25.912 --> 02:27.777
and I'll be running this place.

02:27.847 --> 02:30.315
I'll be shaping and molding
youthful minds

02:30.383 --> 02:32.715
into a focused worldview.

02:34.787 --> 02:35.879
Yep.

02:35.955 --> 02:38.981
Ernest P. Worrell,
camp counselor,

02:39.058 --> 02:42.516
an extraordinary thing
to witness.

02:42.595 --> 02:47.396
[Gasping]

02:47.467 --> 02:49.401
Aah!

02:49.469 --> 02:52.302
[Crash]

03:14.961 --> 03:17.293
[Grunting]

03:21.634 --> 03:23.226
Ugh! Ugh!

03:23.303 --> 03:24.736
[Engine stops]

03:24.804 --> 03:26.965
[Birds chirping]

03:31.110 --> 03:33.203
Aah!

03:33.279 --> 03:36.442
[Breathing heavily]

03:39.886 --> 03:44.050
[Engine rumbling]

03:54.234 --> 03:56.794
E-e-e-e-e-w.

04:01.374 --> 04:03.808
[Grunts, water gurgles]

04:03.876 --> 04:06.504
[Straining]

04:06.579 --> 04:09.275
[Water gurgling]

04:10.450 --> 04:12.714
[Straining]

04:12.785 --> 04:15.049
[Water gurgling]

04:15.121 --> 04:16.884
[Straining]

04:16.956 --> 04:18.890
[Water gurgling]

04:18.958 --> 04:22.894
[Straining]

04:22.962 --> 04:24.987
[Water gurgling]

04:25.064 --> 04:26.998
[Straining]

04:27.066 --> 04:29.159
[Water gurgling]

04:29.235 --> 04:31.294
[Straining]

04:31.371 --> 04:32.633
[Water gurgling]

04:32.705 --> 04:33.831
[Grunting]

04:33.906 --> 04:36.704
[Water gurgling]

04:39.379 --> 04:40.368
[Straining]

04:40.446 --> 04:42.846
[Water gurgling]

04:45.418 --> 04:48.080
Ah heh heh heh heh
heh heh heh heh heh heh.

04:51.324 --> 04:55.192
[Porcelain creaking]

04:56.596 --> 04:57.858
[Toilet flushes]

04:57.930 --> 05:00.490
<i>Aaaaah!</i>

05:02.535 --> 05:08.303
[Boys cheering]

05:19.585 --> 05:21.780
Okay, off the bus!
Off the bus!

05:21.854 --> 05:24.049
Come on! Let's go!
Let's go! Let's go!

05:24.123 --> 05:25.784
Get a line.
Get a line going.

05:25.858 --> 05:27.257
Get a line going.
Let's go.

05:27.327 --> 05:29.056
Let's go.
Move quick. Move it.

05:29.128 --> 05:30.618
Let's go, gentlemen!

05:33.533 --> 05:35.467
Let's go!
Move it out!

05:35.535 --> 05:39.130
Hey, fellas.
Welcome to Kamp Kikakee.

05:39.205 --> 05:41.139
I've got everything fixed up
for you at the cabins,

05:41.207 --> 05:42.572
know what I mean?

05:42.642 --> 05:44.576
Well, look who's here, huh?
Just like old times, huh?

05:44.644 --> 05:46.635
Yeah. Remember all the
fun we had last summer?

05:46.713 --> 05:48.943
Hey, let's start things off
right. What do you say?

05:49.015 --> 05:50.380
Mm-hmm.

05:50.450 --> 05:53.817
[Laughter]

05:53.886 --> 05:54.818
My ha...

05:54.887 --> 05:56.320
My ha...
my... ha...

05:56.389 --> 05:58.323
my hand... hands!

05:58.391 --> 06:01.588
You got a bad attitude,
son.

06:01.661 --> 06:03.891
<i>Let's go! Let's go!
Move it!</i>

06:03.963 --> 06:05.362
<i>Let's go! Let's go!</i>

06:05.431 --> 06:08.662
[Boys shouting indistinctly]

06:08.735 --> 06:10.999
<i>Straighten up these lines.
Come on. Let's go.</i>

06:18.344 --> 06:20.335
Men...

06:20.413 --> 06:23.871
Welcome to another great summer
here at Kamp Kikakee!

06:23.950 --> 06:26.180
[Boys cheering]

06:26.252 --> 06:29.483
Right here
on this very ground,

06:29.555 --> 06:32.854
Indians once tested
their young braves

06:32.925 --> 06:36.292
and taught them the ways
of the forest.

06:36.362 --> 06:39.957
<i>And right here, you'll be
tested and taught, too,</i>

06:40.032 --> 06:43.024
just as they were hundreds
of years ago...

06:43.102 --> 06:44.262
swimming...

06:44.337 --> 06:48.034
<i>fire building, cooking,
camping...</i>

06:48.107 --> 06:50.598
archery,
wilderness survival.

06:50.676 --> 06:54.112
<i>For those of you who accept
the challenge,</i>

06:54.180 --> 06:59.880
there'll be a ceremony
of the blade... the stone...

06:59.952 --> 07:01.214
and the arrow.

07:01.287 --> 07:02.879
All right, guys...
Let's go!

07:02.955 --> 07:04.923
[Boys cheering]

07:10.563 --> 07:11.723
<i>Man: Hup!</i>

07:11.798 --> 07:13.060
<i>Hup!</i>

07:13.132 --> 07:15.657
<i>Hup! Hup!</i>

07:15.735 --> 07:17.202
<i>Hup! And up!</i>

07:17.270 --> 07:19.204
All right, hit the deck...
push-ups.

07:19.272 --> 07:20.967
Crank out 10.

07:21.040 --> 07:22.007
Ready...

07:22.074 --> 07:23.541
One!

07:23.609 --> 07:24.769
Two!

07:24.844 --> 07:25.776
Three!

07:25.845 --> 07:27.312
<i>Four!</i>

07:27.380 --> 07:29.507
<i>Five!</i>

07:29.582 --> 07:30.606
<i>Six!</i>

07:30.683 --> 07:31.980
<i>Seven!</i>

07:34.887 --> 07:36.912
<i>Nine...</i>

07:40.393 --> 07:41.724
Morning, Ernest.

07:41.794 --> 07:43.625
Oh, hi, Miss St. Cloud.

07:43.696 --> 07:44.663
<i>Um...</i>

07:44.730 --> 07:49.030
The sun rides high...

07:49.101 --> 07:55.040
in... its path...
across the heavens.

07:55.107 --> 08:00.170
Where... is the red...

08:00.246 --> 08:02.407
chaise lounge?

08:02.482 --> 08:04.712
<i>Ernest, what I
came down here for is...</i>

08:04.784 --> 08:07.150
<i>You know, engineering
your lifeguard stand</i>

08:07.220 --> 08:08.949
is an important business.

08:09.021 --> 08:11.785
You have got to figure
your angles just right.

08:11.858 --> 08:14.827
<i>Course, I won't always be
fixin' things around here.</i>

08:14.894 --> 08:17.988
One day I will be
a full-fledged counselor.

08:18.064 --> 08:20.931
I have learned all the steps
in the path of the brave,

08:21.000 --> 08:23.161
I have memorized
the handbook,

08:23.236 --> 08:27.002
<i>and I learned
the Kikakee sign language.</i>

08:27.073 --> 08:30.474
If only they'd give a fella
a chance.

08:30.543 --> 08:33.010
I'm sure they will,
Ernest.

08:33.078 --> 08:34.511
Nuh-uh.

08:34.580 --> 08:36.548
But the real reason
I'm here

08:36.616 --> 08:39.346
is to see if you've gotten
all your shots.

08:39.418 --> 08:40.679
[Chuckles]

08:40.753 --> 08:42.015
Shots?

08:42.087 --> 08:44.352
[Chuckles] Yeah...

08:44.423 --> 08:46.857
Okay.

08:46.926 --> 08:49.053
How's that grandfather
of yours nowadays?

08:49.128 --> 08:50.891
I haven't seen him around
lately.

08:50.963 --> 08:52.555
Oh, he's out at his place.

08:52.632 --> 08:56.124
I worry about him sometimes.
He's so old.

08:56.202 --> 08:59.262
But these woods are
his home.

08:59.338 --> 09:02.205
Yeah, he's a wise man.
[Chuckles]

09:02.275 --> 09:05.176
Doesn't believe in
modern things like... shots.

09:05.244 --> 09:06.336
[Chuckles]

09:06.412 --> 09:07.504
That's right.

09:07.580 --> 09:10.242
He lives by the old ways.

09:10.316 --> 09:13.911
In fact, he thinks I'm
wasting time studying medicine.

09:13.986 --> 09:16.011
Shouldn't you, uh,
have a little more practice

09:16.088 --> 09:18.181
before you go around
stickin' needles in people?

09:18.257 --> 09:21.021
[Chuckles]
I've had lots of practice.

09:21.093 --> 09:25.029
If I keep doing it,
I might even get good at it.

09:25.097 --> 09:26.394
[Pop]

09:26.465 --> 09:27.932
[Swallows]

09:28.000 --> 09:30.969
See? A... cold, wet nose.
Color's good.

09:31.037 --> 09:32.129
[Sniffs]

09:32.204 --> 09:34.104
No fever.
[Chuckles]

09:34.173 --> 09:35.504
Come on, now, Ernest.

09:35.575 --> 09:38.271
You know this isn't
going to hurt...

09:38.344 --> 09:40.312
much.

09:40.379 --> 09:42.745
I can take it,
Miss St. Cloud.

09:42.815 --> 09:45.875
Real men can take it,
and I'm a real man...

09:45.952 --> 09:50.013
a man with a hearty smile,
a stout back...

09:50.089 --> 09:53.650
with grit in his teeth
and nails in his knuckles,

09:53.726 --> 09:56.388
a man who has never
tasted quiche...

09:56.462 --> 09:58.555
Is that
your smallest needle?

09:58.631 --> 10:00.394
<i>I did it!</i>

10:00.466 --> 10:02.491
I took the Lindbergh baby!

10:02.568 --> 10:05.332
I am Josef Mengele!

10:05.404 --> 10:08.965
Owwwwww!

10:09.041 --> 10:11.771
[Papers rustling]

10:11.844 --> 10:13.675
Well, as you men know,

10:13.746 --> 10:16.237
our camp's been selected
by the governor's staff

10:16.315 --> 10:19.478
to take part in his, uh, program
for disadvantaged youngsters.

10:19.552 --> 10:21.679
He calls it, uh,
"Operation: Second Chance. "

10:21.754 --> 10:23.745
Some camps have
all the luck.

10:23.823 --> 10:28.157
And I just got notification that the second-chancers
are gonna be ready to be picked up today,

10:28.227 --> 10:29.888
and I wanted you guys
to be prepared for it.

10:29.962 --> 10:31.020
Better hide
your wallets.

10:31.097 --> 10:33.065
Yeah, and get out
your brass knuckles.

10:33.132 --> 10:35.259
We're already short-handed. How are
we gonna handle those delinquents?

10:35.334 --> 10:37.131
Oh, they're not
delinquents.

10:37.203 --> 10:39.967
They're just boys from a bit
rougher environment than most of us.

10:40.039 --> 10:41.506
You mean
underage criminals.

10:41.574 --> 10:43.132
No, they're not.

10:43.209 --> 10:45.643
They're all residents of
the State Institute For Boys,

10:45.711 --> 10:47.178
but they're not criminals.

10:47.246 --> 10:49.510
Stennis, I'm gonna let you
be their counselor.

10:49.582 --> 10:51.516
Why do I get stuck
with them?

10:51.584 --> 10:53.381
Because you've got
the most experience.

10:53.452 --> 10:55.215
Besides, after you get
to know those boys...

10:55.287 --> 10:57.016
Oh, I'm not gonna take
any crap off of them.

10:57.089 --> 10:59.023
If they get out of line,
I'm gonna knock 'em back in.

10:59.091 --> 11:01.218
<i>Ross, Ross...
listen to me.</i>

11:01.293 --> 11:02.225
<i>Just do the best
you can.</i>

11:02.294 --> 11:04.262
<i>If you can't handle it,</i>

11:04.330 --> 11:06.662
<i>- [Bones crack] We'll have no
choice. We'll have to send them back.</i>

11:06.732 --> 11:09.462
Oh, I can handle 'em
all right.

11:09.535 --> 11:13.801
Yeah, a little discipline is
probably just what they need.

11:13.873 --> 11:15.534
<i>Uh, Ernest,
will you take the bus over</i>

11:15.608 --> 11:17.200
<i>and get those
second-chancers for me?</i>

11:17.276 --> 11:19.836
[Creaking]
Aah!

11:19.912 --> 11:21.174
[Thud, glass breaking]

11:21.247 --> 11:22.908
[Engine rumbling]

11:24.817 --> 11:27.980
<i># Bad luck and me,
we are old friends #</i>

11:28.054 --> 11:31.956
<i># Dealt me the losing hand
once again #</i>

11:32.024 --> 11:36.927
<i># Now I'm doin' time,
and time ain't kind #</i>

11:36.996 --> 11:40.193
<i># Sun comes up,
but it don't ever shine #</i>

11:40.266 --> 11:42.894
Boy, I can't wait
to get outta here.

11:42.968 --> 11:45.493
Anyplace is better
than this dump.

11:45.571 --> 11:47.732
Shut up, you two.

11:47.807 --> 11:48.865
Last warning...

11:48.941 --> 11:51.569
you get out of line,
and you don't go.

11:51.644 --> 11:53.077
Ooh.

11:53.145 --> 11:54.908
[Engine revs, brakes squeak]

11:54.980 --> 11:57.574
<i>Man:
All boys in Section 6,</i>

11:57.650 --> 11:59.743
<i>report immediately
to the exercise yard.</i>

11:59.819 --> 12:01.013
Hi, fellas.

12:02.655 --> 12:04.122
Of learnin' the ways
of the forest

12:04.190 --> 12:06.522
<i>and the path of the brave
and that sort of thing?</i>

12:06.592 --> 12:10.221
If you ask me, this second-chance
stuff is a total waste of time,

12:10.296 --> 12:11.558
Mister, uh...

12:11.630 --> 12:13.894
Oh, uh, Worrell...
Ernest P. Worrell.

12:13.966 --> 12:17.026
<i>I don't envy whoever has to
look after this bunch of punks.</i>

12:17.103 --> 12:19.594
They're trouble
all the way.

12:19.672 --> 12:23.039
My motto is,
"I never met a bad kid. "

12:23.109 --> 12:26.977
Then let me introduce you
to some.

12:27.046 --> 12:29.776
These misfits were selected
by their ward officers

12:29.849 --> 12:31.612
as those most in need
of help.

12:31.684 --> 12:33.845
This is the ringleader,
Bobby Wayne.

12:33.919 --> 12:36.410
He's been in and out
of institutions like this

12:36.489 --> 12:37.581
since he was 11.

12:37.656 --> 12:39.715
Since I was 9.

12:39.792 --> 12:41.350
And this is Crutchfield,

12:41.427 --> 12:44.362
12 years old
and already a master thief.

12:44.430 --> 12:46.955
It's like a gift
or somethin'.

12:47.032 --> 12:48.795
Well, thanks.

12:48.868 --> 12:51.063
Uh, here's Danny Simpson.

12:51.137 --> 12:54.402
He comes from a long line
of troublemakers.

12:54.473 --> 12:55.667
It's a family tradition.

12:55.741 --> 12:59.177
I've got a reputation
to uphold.

12:59.245 --> 13:04.979
And the Albert Einstein
of this institution,

13:05.050 --> 13:06.642
<i>Chip O zgood.</i>

13:09.889 --> 13:12.824
Butch "Too Cool" Vargas.

13:12.892 --> 13:13.881
[Door opens, closes]

13:13.959 --> 13:17.360
Hey, Moose!
Hurry up, man!

13:19.398 --> 13:22.834
It's Moustafa,
the runt of the litter.

13:22.902 --> 13:24.460
I told you...

13:24.537 --> 13:26.801
it's dangerous to run
with things in your mouth.

13:26.872 --> 13:28.464
Yes, ma'am.
I'm sorry.

13:28.541 --> 13:32.170
Uh, well, uh, all aboard
that's goin' ashore.

13:34.180 --> 13:36.307
Here we go...
life in the fast lane.

13:36.382 --> 13:39.283
Whoa. Nice bus.

13:39.351 --> 13:40.545
Does it run?

13:44.723 --> 13:47.351
Boy, we're gonna have
a great time this summer.

13:47.426 --> 13:49.656
We got boating
and, uh, campin'

13:49.728 --> 13:52.322
and swimmin'
and Indian Lore,

13:52.398 --> 13:54.866
and I've got everything
fixed up for you, too.

13:54.934 --> 13:55.866
Guess who!

13:55.935 --> 13:56.867
[Laughter]

13:56.936 --> 13:58.801
Uh, let's see.
Uh, Bobby?

13:58.871 --> 13:59.963
- No, no.
- No. - No.

14:00.039 --> 14:02.064
Uh, um, not Moose.

14:02.141 --> 14:03.904
It's not Ozgood.

14:06.245 --> 14:09.373
Now, don't tell me, really. Really,
I'm really good at this. I really am.

14:09.448 --> 14:11.439
[Engine revving]

14:14.553 --> 14:16.544
- Let's see...
- Turn left, Ernest!

14:16.622 --> 14:18.681
[Horn blares]

14:18.757 --> 14:20.520
[Tires screech]

14:21.994 --> 14:22.926
Uh, Vargas.

14:22.995 --> 14:23.927
No!

14:23.996 --> 14:24.985
No? Okay.

14:27.733 --> 14:30.497
Hey, guys, when
the new campers get here,

14:30.569 --> 14:34.733
let's give 'em a big
Kamp Kikakee welcome, okay?!

14:34.807 --> 14:37.207
Oh, the leader's
the biggest geek of them all.

14:39.678 --> 14:41.908
Not Crutchfield.
Crutchfield! That's it!

14:41.981 --> 14:44.415
[Laughter]

14:44.483 --> 14:46.974
I knew it was Crutchfield
all along.

14:47.052 --> 14:48.417
Ernest!

14:48.487 --> 14:50.580
[Brakes squeak, glass breaks]

14:50.656 --> 14:53.284
[Hinges squeak, thud]

14:53.359 --> 14:55.884
[Laughter]

14:55.961 --> 14:57.394
What happened?

14:57.463 --> 14:59.226
Ernest wasn't watching
the road.

14:59.298 --> 15:02.495
All right, you guys move out.
This ain't a pleasure cruise.

15:02.568 --> 15:03.728
[Laughter]

15:03.802 --> 15:05.133
[Grunts]

15:05.204 --> 15:06.136
Come on. Move.

15:06.205 --> 15:07.866
You guys, line up.

15:12.244 --> 15:16.078
Frankly, I'm disappointed
in you, Ernest.

15:16.148 --> 15:19.982
<i>I give you a simple task to
do, and this is what I get.</i>

15:20.052 --> 15:23.419
<i>I don't know how you can
ever expect to be a counselor.</i>

15:23.489 --> 15:25.150
You're right,
Mr. Tipton.

15:25.224 --> 15:27.624
He's just not
counselor material.

15:27.693 --> 15:28.955
[Coughs]

15:29.028 --> 15:30.723
Uh, Mist... it's...
it's not my fault.

15:30.796 --> 15:31.820
All right, let's go.

15:31.897 --> 15:34.798
<i>I was... [Coughs]</i>

15:34.867 --> 15:37.597
I mean I was...
[Sighs]

15:37.670 --> 15:40.764
I'm sorry, Mr. Tipton.
I'll try to do better.

15:40.839 --> 15:42.500
[Sighs]

15:45.878 --> 15:48.142
Gosh.

15:48.213 --> 15:49.942
Let's go.
Keep it moving.

15:50.015 --> 15:52.745
[Birds chirping]

15:52.818 --> 15:54.285
[Exhales deeply]

15:54.353 --> 15:56.947
Well, this is it...
your home away from prison.

15:57.022 --> 16:00.082
Stennis, the delinquents
you ordered...

16:00.159 --> 16:01.319
all yours.

16:01.393 --> 16:02.724
Have fun, guys.

16:05.464 --> 16:09.764
<i>The name's Stennis...
Counselor Stennis to you.</i>

16:09.835 --> 16:12.269
Let's go. Move it.
Inside.

16:16.442 --> 16:19.775
<i>All right,
get this place cleaned up.</i>

16:19.845 --> 16:22.575
<i>Mess hall, 10 minutes.</i>

16:22.648 --> 16:24.309
What a dump!

16:26.285 --> 16:28.776
[Indistinct conversations]

16:33.525 --> 16:36.289
[All talking]

16:36.362 --> 16:39.559
[Talking subsides]

16:39.631 --> 16:41.496
Here comes the riffraff.

16:41.567 --> 16:45.003
<i>Looks like
"Project: Last Chance" to me.</i>

16:45.070 --> 16:47.937
Come on, gang.
Follow me.

16:53.112 --> 16:54.443
Well, well.

16:54.513 --> 16:58.005
Looks like daddy's little
gentlemen are glad to see us.

16:58.083 --> 17:01.575
<i>Yeah, if white bread could
talk, it'd fit in right here.</i>

17:01.653 --> 17:03.382
There's a lot of love
in this room.

17:03.455 --> 17:06.117
I can feel it,
and it's a beautiful thing.

17:06.191 --> 17:08.659
Yeah. I'm moved.

17:08.727 --> 17:10.058
[Liquid bubbling]

17:10.128 --> 17:11.323
Hi, fellas.

17:11.396 --> 17:13.592
Boy, do I have
something special prepared

17:13.665 --> 17:15.098
for your first day at camp.

17:15.166 --> 17:16.828
- [Fly buzzing]
- Hey, what is this stuff?

17:16.902 --> 17:19.063
Oh, it's sugar puffs
with a gravy casserole

17:19.137 --> 17:22.539
with just a cuwcah of bologna-walnut
fudge in a pork marinade.

17:22.608 --> 17:26.044
I think it'll be a real boost
for the fiber of American youth.

17:26.111 --> 17:27.042
Isn't it, Jake?

17:27.112 --> 17:28.238
Why, of course it is.

17:28.313 --> 17:30.713
Doesn't smell too bad.

17:30.783 --> 17:32.944
[Buzzing continues]

17:33.018 --> 17:34.315
Yeah, that's the guy

17:34.386 --> 17:37.878
who once ate two pounds
of modeling clay.

17:41.260 --> 17:43.091
Modeling clay!

17:43.162 --> 17:44.993
Yellow modeling clay!

17:45.064 --> 17:47.555
That's the secret ingredient
to eggs erroneous.

17:47.633 --> 17:50.500
We re-fuse the proteins
like bullion.

17:52.671 --> 17:55.435
Of course it would!
Uh, get back to work!

17:55.507 --> 17:57.737
Modeling clay...

17:57.810 --> 18:00.574
Modeling clay.

18:00.646 --> 18:03.046
[Indistinct conversations]

18:05.684 --> 18:06.616
Ugh!

18:06.685 --> 18:07.879
Oh! Ho ho!

18:07.953 --> 18:10.513
Did the little fellow
fall down and go boom?

18:10.589 --> 18:13.387
Looks like he needs
special classes in walking.

18:13.459 --> 18:16.428
Hey, dipstick, you ever pick on anybody
your own size, or just little kids?

18:16.495 --> 18:18.395
Hey, can I help it
if the kid can't walk?

18:18.464 --> 18:20.159
It was an accident.

18:20.232 --> 18:21.494
Accident, huh?

18:21.567 --> 18:23.000
Well... whoops!

18:23.068 --> 18:25.468
What do you know?
Another accident!

18:25.537 --> 18:27.402
There must be something
going around.

18:27.473 --> 18:28.405
[Laughter]

18:28.474 --> 18:29.441
Ugh!

18:29.508 --> 18:32.500
[All shouting indistinctly]

18:38.517 --> 18:41.486
[Shouting continues]

18:41.553 --> 18:43.487
Stop it!
Stop it!

18:43.555 --> 18:44.647
[Shouting stops]

18:44.723 --> 18:47.658
What do you think
you're doing?

18:47.726 --> 18:48.693
- This!
- This!

18:48.760 --> 18:51.957
[Shouting resumes]

18:54.333 --> 18:55.265
[Thud]

18:55.334 --> 18:56.926
[Shouting stops]

18:57.002 --> 18:58.435
[Grunting]

18:58.504 --> 19:01.098
<i>Oh, my God.
He can't breathe!</i>

19:01.173 --> 19:02.970
Well, let's do something.
Come on.

19:03.041 --> 19:04.406
[Mumbling]

19:04.476 --> 19:06.671
Come on, guys! I got him!
I got him! Guys, I got him!

19:06.745 --> 19:07.677
Back up!

19:07.746 --> 19:09.145
Hold steady, now!

19:09.214 --> 19:11.682
[Mumbling]

19:11.750 --> 19:12.842
[Thud]

19:12.918 --> 19:14.180
[Grunts]

19:14.253 --> 19:16.687
[Thud]

19:18.624 --> 19:20.990
[Thud, Ernest groans]

19:21.059 --> 19:23.721
[Rubble falling]

19:32.971 --> 19:34.734
This ditch has got to go

19:34.806 --> 19:36.967
all the way to the waterfront,
gentlemen.

19:37.042 --> 19:39.977
Maybe by then some of the fight
will be out of your system.

19:40.045 --> 19:42.036
Man, this isn't fair.
They started it.

19:42.114 --> 19:43.877
Yeah, man!
They tripped Moose!

19:43.949 --> 19:45.541
You boys have got to learn...

19:45.617 --> 19:48.984
if you play... you pay.

19:53.692 --> 19:55.557
Hey, don't work
too hard, fellas.

19:55.627 --> 19:57.219
Yeah, life's a ditch,
guys.

19:57.296 --> 20:00.060
Can you dig it?

20:00.132 --> 20:04.034
I just want one clean shot
at blondie.

20:04.102 --> 20:06.002
[Grunting]

20:10.576 --> 20:11.873
<i>Now, Eddie, if you don't
stir it, it'll clot on ya.</i>

20:11.944 --> 20:13.809
[Sniffs]
Something burnin'?

20:13.879 --> 20:15.369
Here. Look what we got
for ya.

20:15.447 --> 20:16.607
E-e-w.

20:16.682 --> 20:17.944
Look at that.

20:18.016 --> 20:21.850
Jake's specialty du jour...
eggs erroneous.

20:21.920 --> 20:25.651
It's made with powdered eggs
and 17 herbs and spices

20:25.724 --> 20:28.124
smuggled into this country
by Tibetan monks.

20:28.193 --> 20:32.027
Ernest, I want you to cut
yourself a big knock

20:32.097 --> 20:33.758
out of
these eggs erroneous.

20:33.832 --> 20:35.800
No, I-I can't eat
on an empty stomach.

20:35.867 --> 20:37.198
Why,
of course you can.

20:37.269 --> 20:39.829
Eddie does, and look at
that rosy glow to his teeth.

20:39.905 --> 20:41.634
[Bell dings]

20:41.707 --> 20:42.969
No.

20:43.041 --> 20:45.100
- Oh, come on, now.
- No.

20:45.177 --> 20:47.611
Now, Ernest, would
somebody dressed like this

20:47.679 --> 20:48.941
lie to you about food?

20:49.014 --> 20:50.879
Fond as I am
of Tibetan cooking,

20:50.949 --> 20:53.509
a hungry lion hunts best,
know what I mean?

20:53.585 --> 20:55.052
Now, come on.
Take you a little bite.

20:55.120 --> 20:56.052
No.

20:56.121 --> 20:57.315
- Come on, now.
- No.

20:57.389 --> 20:58.321
- Open big.
- No.

20:58.390 --> 20:59.414
- Come on.
- No.

20:59.491 --> 21:01.851
- Ernest...
- No!

21:01.927 --> 21:03.087
- Ernest!
- No!

21:03.161 --> 21:04.321
Eddie!

21:04.396 --> 21:06.830
It's time for the plane
to go to hangar.

21:06.898 --> 21:10.129
[Liquid bubbling]

21:10.202 --> 21:11.396
Ow!

21:11.470 --> 21:14.667
[Imitating]
sputtering engine]

21:14.740 --> 21:18.267
[Engine roars]

21:18.343 --> 21:20.811
[Mumbling]

21:24.650 --> 21:26.277
A rabbit, Jake!

21:26.351 --> 21:28.649
We could use a rabbit!

21:28.720 --> 21:30.051
Rabbit!

21:30.122 --> 21:31.714
That's it! A rabbit!

21:31.790 --> 21:34.691
A big, fat rabbit
with all of its shots!

21:34.760 --> 21:36.853
[Gagging]

21:39.631 --> 21:42.532
[Humming]

21:42.601 --> 21:45.365
[Vomiting]

21:52.210 --> 21:54.804
Hey, you boys got a look
all your own.

21:55.914 --> 21:58.178
- Who-oa!
- Should've been ready.

21:58.250 --> 21:59.547
You snooze, you lose.

21:59.618 --> 22:01.552
[Grunts, laughs]

22:01.620 --> 22:02.712
You just watch it!

22:02.788 --> 22:03.982
I'll get you!

22:08.193 --> 22:10.218
Whoa!

22:10.295 --> 22:11.956
Whoo!

22:12.030 --> 22:13.793
Whoa!

22:15.267 --> 22:19.465
[Laughter]

22:19.538 --> 22:21.506
Whoo-hoo!

22:21.573 --> 22:24.974
[Boys cheering]

22:25.043 --> 22:26.237
Whoa!

22:26.311 --> 22:29.041
All right.
Everybody to the line.

22:30.916 --> 22:34.010
[Diving board rattling]

22:34.086 --> 22:36.418
Okay,
everybody in the water.

22:41.560 --> 22:42.492
<i>Wow, this is great!</i>

22:42.561 --> 22:44.188
<i>Come on, Moose!</i>

22:44.262 --> 22:47.663
Moose-tafa... Moose...
whatever they call you...

22:47.733 --> 22:49.997
now.

22:50.068 --> 22:53.765
So... you're the only one
that can't swim, eh?

22:53.839 --> 22:56.433
[Boys shouting]

22:56.508 --> 22:59.170
No... please.

22:59.244 --> 23:01.439
Well, you're gonna learn...
the Stennis way.

23:01.513 --> 23:03.003
No!
[Crying] No!

23:03.081 --> 23:04.070
I can't swim!

23:04.149 --> 23:05.116
<i>Help!</i>

23:05.183 --> 23:06.707
<i>Somebody help!</i>

23:09.621 --> 23:10.553
[Thud]

23:10.622 --> 23:12.920
<i>Help!</i>

23:12.991 --> 23:14.424
[Coughing]

23:22.167 --> 23:24.158
Thanks, Ernest.
I could've made it.

23:24.236 --> 23:25.567
Glad to help out.

23:29.207 --> 23:31.266
Well, meatheads,
we're gonna try this again.

23:31.343 --> 23:33.607
<i>This time it's to the end
of the lake and back.</i>

23:33.678 --> 23:34.610
Look.

23:34.679 --> 23:36.943
<i>Everybody in the water.</i>

23:37.015 --> 23:38.482
[All grunting]

23:38.550 --> 23:39.482
Whoa!

23:39.551 --> 23:41.382
Yeah!

23:41.453 --> 23:42.442
[Laughter]

23:42.521 --> 23:44.318
My leg.
My I... [Coughs]

23:44.389 --> 23:46.550
He's learning to swim
the Stennis way.

23:46.625 --> 23:47.649
[Laughter]

23:47.726 --> 23:48.715
[Coughs]

23:48.794 --> 23:51.058
My leg! Aah!

23:51.129 --> 23:52.721
[Crickets chirp]

23:52.798 --> 23:55.096
It's a shame about
Counselor Stennis' accident.

23:55.167 --> 23:56.259
It was no accident.

23:56.334 --> 23:57.824
I don't know
what to do.

23:57.903 --> 24:00.167
I mean, it's important to make
the experiment work.

24:00.238 --> 24:01.865
Send 'em back!
Get 'em out of here!

24:01.940 --> 24:04.670
These guys have no respect
for anything.

24:04.743 --> 24:07.769
The main problem is we're
already short-handed.

24:07.846 --> 24:11.441
<i>What we need is
another counselor.</i>

24:11.516 --> 24:13.177
Hey...

24:13.251 --> 24:15.276
I got an idea.

24:16.988 --> 24:19.013
<i>Ernest, uh,
have you ever had</i>

24:19.090 --> 24:21.251
<i>any group-leadership
experience?</i>

24:21.326 --> 24:23.157
Uh, I had
an ant farm once.

24:23.228 --> 24:24.820
Close enough.

24:24.896 --> 24:26.830
How would you like to be
a counselor?

24:26.898 --> 24:29.458
Are you kiddin'?
Y-You mean a-a real counselor?

24:29.534 --> 24:32.094
A counselor like you guys,
a counselor?

24:32.170 --> 24:33.797
Just like us, Ernest.

24:33.872 --> 24:37.035
Uh, oh, Mr. Tipton, uh,
that's great.

24:37.108 --> 24:39.770
And... and I'll do
a great job... a great job...

24:39.845 --> 24:41.870
and I'll do
my regular work, too.

24:41.947 --> 24:44.939
Oh, I can't believe it's
true... me, a counselor.

24:45.016 --> 24:47.177
Oh, a-a real counselor.

24:47.252 --> 24:49.379
I can't believe it.
Oh, thank you, Mr. Tipton.

24:49.454 --> 24:50.978
<i>Thank you,
thank you, thank you.</i>

24:51.056 --> 24:53.354
<i>A real counselor...
a really, really real, real,</i>

24:53.425 --> 24:55.416
really, really, really,
real counselor.

24:55.494 --> 24:57.519
<i>Thank you, Mr. Tipton.
Thank you. [Smooches]</i>

24:57.596 --> 24:59.894
[Metal rattling]

25:02.467 --> 25:04.196
As your counselor,

25:04.269 --> 25:06.965
I will be taking you
deep into the forest

25:07.038 --> 25:09.905
in search of actual nature.

25:09.975 --> 25:11.966
<i>We'll be traveling fast,</i>

25:12.043 --> 25:15.342
moving light, keeping our ears
to the grindstone.

25:15.413 --> 25:18.746
<i>So stay together,
be remindful of the weather,</i>

25:18.817 --> 25:20.114
and, for Heaven's sakes,

25:20.185 --> 25:23.177
don't pick it,
or it will never heal.

25:23.255 --> 25:24.688
[Metal rattling]

25:24.756 --> 25:27.418
This guy looks like
a walking army-surplus store.

25:27.492 --> 25:28.720
The Salvation Army.

25:28.793 --> 25:31.159
I feel like the blind
are leading the stupid.

25:31.229 --> 25:32.696
What a loser.

25:32.764 --> 25:36.359
[Birds and crickets
chirping]

25:36.434 --> 25:38.459
Hey, Rambo,
where are we goin'?

25:38.537 --> 25:40.334
Maybe he knows
a shortcut.

25:40.405 --> 25:41.667
Maybe we're lost.

25:41.740 --> 25:43.799
What is this,
"Wild Kingdom"?

25:43.875 --> 25:46.935
<i>Ernest: Yeah, boys, isn't it
great to get off the beaten path,</i>

25:47.012 --> 25:49.674
get out where nature
really lives?

25:49.748 --> 25:51.909
None of that theme-park stuff
here, know what I mean?

25:51.983 --> 25:54.281
Come on, Ernest.
You're gonna get us lost.

25:54.352 --> 25:56.912
Well, we were lost
for weeks in Nam.

25:56.988 --> 26:01.118
I was under fire,
my body riddled with shrapnel,

26:01.192 --> 26:03.251
<i>malaria, mono...</i>

26:03.328 --> 26:04.955
wet socks.

26:05.030 --> 26:07.294
So... how do we get out
of here?

26:07.365 --> 26:10.528
Yeah, we were... we were
rough, tough, and hard to bluff.

26:10.602 --> 26:11.796
Men of iron,

26:11.870 --> 26:13.633
men who had never
tasted quiche.

26:13.705 --> 26:14.933
Really?

26:15.006 --> 26:16.769
Well, you couldn't even
get quiche in nam.

26:16.841 --> 26:19.810
Gosh, Ernest, I guess
you've done about everything.

26:19.878 --> 26:22.676
Some men try,
and some men die.

26:22.747 --> 26:25.477
[Snaps fingers]
Hey.

26:25.550 --> 26:29.111
[Rumbling, explosions]

26:55.547 --> 26:57.139
He's waitin' on you.

26:59.751 --> 27:01.343
Mr. Blatz... Mr. Blatz?

27:01.419 --> 27:03.785
It looks like we're making
progress, sir.

27:03.855 --> 27:06.449
This sample is
over 20% petrocite.

27:06.524 --> 27:09.982
20%. Well, this little expedition
may be worth something yet.

27:10.061 --> 27:11.187
Talk to me, George.

27:11.262 --> 27:12.661
Well, Mr. Blatz,

27:12.731 --> 27:14.961
I've been studying the results
of the exploratories,

27:15.033 --> 27:18.799
and the big hit is right here
at Kamp Kikakee.

27:18.870 --> 27:19.802
[Beep]

27:19.871 --> 27:23.329
<i>Man:
Blatz here yet?</i>

27:23.408 --> 27:26.275
[Exhales deeply]

27:30.749 --> 27:32.307
Did you get it?

27:32.384 --> 27:33.817
No.

27:33.885 --> 27:35.944
I couldn't get
the old Indian to budge.

27:36.021 --> 27:38.080
Sherman, he might as
well be on another planet.

27:38.156 --> 27:40.818
I don't want
your excuses.

27:40.892 --> 27:42.553
I want results.

27:43.862 --> 27:45.887
All right, Sherman,
I'll give it another try.

27:45.964 --> 27:48.023
Do I have to remind you,
Mr. Blatz,

27:48.099 --> 27:51.967
just how valuable petrocite
is to the space program

27:52.037 --> 27:56.201
and every other defense
contractor in the world?

27:56.274 --> 27:58.208
What we're
talking about here

27:58.276 --> 28:00.710
is the largest deposit
ever found.

28:00.779 --> 28:03.907
There are millions
at stake here...

28:03.982 --> 28:06.974
so why don't you get your
tight, little lawyer's butt

28:07.052 --> 28:10.544
over to the camp
and get me that lease?

28:14.259 --> 28:15.726
Learning to make a fire

28:15.794 --> 28:18.456
without matches and gasoline
is essential.

28:18.530 --> 28:19.827
[Birds chirping]

28:19.898 --> 28:23.334
You need to know
the basic physics of friction.

28:25.170 --> 28:26.933
It's a simple rule
of nature.

28:27.005 --> 28:30.736
You know, you can make
a fire this way.

28:30.809 --> 28:32.777
Boy, is it painful.

28:32.844 --> 28:34.778
Ow!

28:34.846 --> 28:39.112
[Leaves rustling,
metal rattling]

28:39.184 --> 28:41.243
Do you believe
this guy?

28:41.319 --> 28:43.651
Boys, look!

28:43.722 --> 28:45.952
A family of badgers.

28:46.024 --> 28:49.050
Just as I promised you...
actual nature.

28:49.127 --> 28:52.722
El Badgerus Maximus Ferocius
with young.

28:52.797 --> 28:54.958
The young look just like
the regular badgers,

28:55.033 --> 28:56.295
only smaller.

28:56.367 --> 28:58.460
Now, here's a lesson
to be learned...

28:58.536 --> 29:00.527
although they look cute
and cuddly,

29:00.605 --> 29:04.439
don't ever, ever do this
to a family of badgers.

29:04.509 --> 29:05.942
Aba daba daba daba
daba daba daba!

29:06.010 --> 29:07.068
Aaaaah!

29:07.145 --> 29:09.477
[Badgers growling, chomping]

29:09.547 --> 29:11.378
[Ernest screaming]

29:16.921 --> 29:19.913
All right!
Time to practice first aid!

29:19.991 --> 29:22.482
- Hey, yeah, let's go! Come on!
- Yeah!

29:24.562 --> 29:27.122
[Muffled voice] This is a real
nice field dressing, fellas,

29:27.198 --> 29:28.529
but I can't breathe.

29:28.600 --> 29:29.862
[Muffled laughter]

29:29.934 --> 29:32.095
W-What's that, Ernest?
I-I can't hear you.

29:32.170 --> 29:33.831
You've got gauze
in your mouth.

29:33.905 --> 29:35.998
I said I can't breathe!

29:36.074 --> 29:38.338
Get me out of here, fast!

29:38.409 --> 29:40.206
D-Did you say fast?

29:40.278 --> 29:41.472
Uh-huh.

29:41.546 --> 29:43.138
- Uh-huh.
- [Laughter]

29:43.214 --> 29:44.511
Okay, no... no problem.

29:44.582 --> 29:46.846
We'll have you
out of there in a jiffy.

29:46.918 --> 29:48.749
[Birds chirping]

29:51.122 --> 29:53.317
[Keys jingle,
engine turns over]

29:55.994 --> 29:57.928
Just stick tight.
We'll be out of there.

29:57.996 --> 29:59.122
<i>Just hold on.</i>

30:02.367 --> 30:03.925
[Engine revs]

30:04.502 --> 30:05.662
Mnh! Mnh!

30:07.105 --> 30:08.003
Mnh! Mnh!

30:10.208 --> 30:11.505
[Muffled shouting]

30:12.677 --> 30:15.271
[Shouting continues]

30:18.783 --> 30:20.978
Ahhh.

30:22.587 --> 30:24.714
[Groans]

30:24.789 --> 30:26.916
[Thud]

30:26.991 --> 30:28.253
What happened?

30:28.326 --> 30:31.454
Uh, Ernest was teaching us
first aid.

30:31.529 --> 30:34.225
Well... at least
nobody was hurt.

30:34.299 --> 30:36.460
[Ernest groans]

30:38.303 --> 30:41.636
Look, Miss St. Cloud,
how can I convince you here?

30:41.706 --> 30:45.733
This is the chance of a lifetime
for you and your grandfather.

30:45.810 --> 30:52.477
Now, he will receive 5%...
5% royalty, chief...

30:52.550 --> 30:54.211
on every ounce of petrocite

30:54.285 --> 30:56.947
that Krader Mining
pulls from the ground.

30:57.021 --> 31:01.014
Now, we're talking
a lot of money here...

31:01.092 --> 31:04.823
well over a million dollars
in just the first year.

31:04.896 --> 31:08.662
All right,
I'll try again...

31:08.733 --> 31:09.893
Thank you.

31:09.968 --> 31:12.436
But I know my grandfather.

31:12.503 --> 31:15.836
You will have great wealth

31:15.907 --> 31:19.843
if you let these men
own the land.

31:19.911 --> 31:22.505
[Speaking
native language]

31:28.419 --> 31:31.513
He says,
"Who can own a tree?

31:31.589 --> 31:33.580
"Who can own a rock?

31:33.658 --> 31:37.287
Only the great spirit. "

31:37.362 --> 31:39.296
[Birds chirping]

31:39.364 --> 31:41.423
Mr. Blatz,
this camp is here

31:41.499 --> 31:44.696
because these were
ancient ceremonial grounds.

31:44.769 --> 31:48.535
My grandfather and I are
the last members of our tribe.

31:48.606 --> 31:52.565
This is part
of a sacred trust.

31:52.644 --> 31:56.375
<i>My grandfather thinks
of those boys as young braves</i>

31:56.447 --> 32:00.042
who keep alive the tradition
of our ancestors.

32:00.118 --> 32:01.551
[Inhales deeply]

32:01.619 --> 32:03.177
[Briefcase clicks]

32:03.254 --> 32:05.586
I'm sorry to hear that,
Miss St. Cloud...

32:07.725 --> 32:09.989
...but have a nice day.

32:17.402 --> 32:20.462
[Indistinct conversations]

32:20.538 --> 32:23.200
Hey, Bobby Wayne,
let's see that.

32:23.274 --> 32:25.299
Now, that is a real beauty.

32:25.376 --> 32:26.775
[Click]

32:26.844 --> 32:28.141
Let your old buddy Ernest

32:28.212 --> 32:30.646
show you how to put
a razor edge on that dog.

32:30.715 --> 32:32.273
How 'bout it?

32:32.350 --> 32:34.978
First, you wet the stone.

32:35.053 --> 32:37.453
[Slurps]

32:37.522 --> 32:38.784
Ech!

32:38.856 --> 32:40.721
That's the hard part.

32:40.792 --> 32:42.589
[Smacks lips]

32:42.660 --> 32:45.595
Then you hold the knife
at a perfect 45-degree angle

32:45.663 --> 32:47.790
and run it briskly
down the stone...

32:47.865 --> 32:49.059
[Metal scrapes]

32:49.133 --> 32:52.728
And through the meat
of the hand.

32:52.804 --> 32:54.863
There you go, razor sharp.

32:54.939 --> 32:56.406
Ah heh heh heh heh.

32:56.474 --> 32:58.533
Is that a rabbit
over there?

32:58.609 --> 33:01.874
Owwww.

33:01.946 --> 33:05.882
- First aid?
- First aid.

33:05.950 --> 33:08.214
[Engine rumbling]

33:11.022 --> 33:13.286
Eddie, the way I've got
this figured is...

33:13.358 --> 33:15.690
the new liver-loaf
lunch arranger

33:15.760 --> 33:18.854
can feed the entire camp
in... in two minutes.

33:18.930 --> 33:21.558
L-It slices, it dices,
it juliennes...

33:21.632 --> 33:23.293
and it teaches respect!

33:23.368 --> 33:25.928
Yes, Jake, the liver-loaf
lunch arranger

33:26.004 --> 33:27.904
has taken us
one step closer

33:27.972 --> 33:30.065
to the elusive
eggs erroneous.

33:32.110 --> 33:33.702
Ready, Eddie?!

33:33.778 --> 33:35.473
Lobster bisque!

33:35.546 --> 33:37.411
Lobster bisque, here!
Ready, ready!

33:37.482 --> 33:39.848
[High-pitched voice] No, no,
not the lobster bisque!

33:39.917 --> 33:43.045
[Normal voice] Oh, you don't want
to go in the liver-loaf arranger?

33:43.121 --> 33:44.452
[High-pitched voice] No!

33:44.522 --> 33:46.683
[Normal voice] Okay,
I won't put you in there then.

33:46.758 --> 33:48.726
Get outta here! You and
your sappy friend, too.

33:48.793 --> 33:50.260
[High-pitched voice]
No, no!

33:50.328 --> 33:52.558
<i>Ah ha ha ha ha
ha ha ha ha!</i>

33:52.630 --> 33:54.564
<i>I love crustaceans, Jake.
Put him in.</i>

33:54.632 --> 33:56.566
All right, got it, Jake.
Got it.

33:56.634 --> 33:58.101
<i>Elevate, elevate!</i>

33:58.169 --> 33:59.727
Pretty good, Jake.

33:59.804 --> 34:01.635
Chicken potpie!

34:01.706 --> 34:03.071
Chicken...

34:03.141 --> 34:04.665
[Clucking]

34:04.742 --> 34:06.403
Pot...

34:06.477 --> 34:07.842
Pie!

34:07.912 --> 34:09.208
Chicken potpie, Jake.

34:09.280 --> 34:11.009
<i>Comin' your way, Eddie!
Rockin' fire!</i>

34:11.081 --> 34:12.844
<i>Shoot it, baby!
Shoot it!</i>

34:12.917 --> 34:15.215
<i>Ah ha ha!</i>

34:15.286 --> 34:17.719
[Motor whirring]

34:17.789 --> 34:20.849
I want you to go long
this time, Eddie.

34:20.925 --> 34:22.358
Ready, Jake!

34:22.427 --> 34:25.362
And now for
Fettuccine Alfredo.

34:25.429 --> 34:27.022
Fettuccine Alfredo, Jake.

34:27.098 --> 34:29.896
First, the fettuccine...

34:29.967 --> 34:31.958
And then a little Italian
named Fredo.

34:32.036 --> 34:33.764
[Italian accent]
No, mÃ mma mia!

34:33.838 --> 34:35.533
Not in the liver-loaf
arranger!

34:35.606 --> 34:36.868
[Normal voice]
Of course in there.

34:36.940 --> 34:38.203
<i>Let 'er rip, Jake.</i>

34:38.275 --> 34:40.301
[Motor whirring]

34:40.378 --> 34:42.777
<i>All right! Yeah!</i>

34:42.847 --> 34:43.813
Ech!

34:44.815 --> 34:47.284
[Air hissing]

34:47.351 --> 34:48.612
[Groaning]

34:48.686 --> 34:50.779
[Crickets chirp]

34:50.855 --> 34:55.315
[Straining]

34:55.393 --> 34:58.453
Uhh!
[Breathing heavily]

35:21.619 --> 35:25.487
[Jet engine blasts, roars]

35:27.558 --> 35:28.889
[Whistling]

35:28.960 --> 35:30.291
Aah!

35:30.361 --> 35:32.295
Ah heh heh heh
heh heh heh.

35:32.363 --> 35:34.490
[Sizzling]

35:34.565 --> 35:36.430
Owwwww!

35:36.501 --> 35:38.366
[Gasps] Ugh!

35:40.371 --> 35:42.305
[Metal clanks]

35:42.373 --> 35:44.307
- [Sizzling]
- Oww!

35:44.375 --> 35:45.842
[Chips clinking]

35:45.910 --> 35:47.502
It's all right.

35:47.578 --> 35:49.375
Yeah,
it's okay here...

35:49.447 --> 35:51.438
compared to
the institute.

35:51.516 --> 35:54.246
Yeah. I sort of like
actual nature.

35:54.318 --> 35:56.650
Full boat...
ladies and cowboys.

35:56.721 --> 35:57.813
Aw, man!

35:57.889 --> 35:59.220
That's it for me.

35:59.290 --> 36:01.383
What are y'all doin', huh?

36:01.459 --> 36:02.926
Ahh, poker.

36:02.994 --> 36:05.588
It looks like I'm gonna
have to teach you

36:05.663 --> 36:06.925
a little lesson in gaming.

36:06.998 --> 36:08.590
Put on the eggs, mama,

36:08.666 --> 36:11.965
'cause daddy's gonna bring home
the bacon, know what I mean?

36:12.036 --> 36:14.163
Oh, sure, Ernest.
Hey, deal him in, Oz.

36:14.238 --> 36:15.899
Come on over here,
good luck.

36:15.973 --> 36:19.033
Yeah, I remember once
I was playing dollar ante

36:19.110 --> 36:20.771
with a bunch of roughnecks

36:20.845 --> 36:23.780
from down around
the oil fields of Delacroix.

36:23.848 --> 36:26.817
We were playing
5-card Mexican Gorilla Sweat,

36:26.884 --> 36:28.351
deuces and treses wild,

36:28.419 --> 36:31.877
and, boys, I was catching cards
like I had 12 fingers,

36:31.956 --> 36:33.218
know what I mean?

36:33.291 --> 36:35.088
[Chips clinking]

36:35.159 --> 36:37.252
I get paid on Fridays.

36:37.328 --> 36:40.559
I could let you have
$30 a week.

36:40.631 --> 36:45.364
That means I'd be paid up
in 14 years...

36:45.436 --> 36:48.098
and a couple of months.

36:48.172 --> 36:50.106
Ohh.

36:50.174 --> 36:52.574
[Engine rumbling]

37:00.585 --> 37:02.485
Site four's got to be
cleared tonight,

37:02.553 --> 37:03.815
and they're still in there!

37:03.888 --> 37:06.118
Listen to me! There are
such things as laws.

37:06.190 --> 37:07.487
There are proper channels.

37:07.558 --> 37:09.924
You can't just go into
somebody's house and take...

37:09.994 --> 37:11.461
Hey...

37:11.529 --> 37:13.258
What are you doing here?

37:13.331 --> 37:14.389
<i>They're still in there!</i>

37:14.465 --> 37:16.956
Sherman, can we not give
this family

37:17.034 --> 37:18.626
just a little more time?

37:18.703 --> 37:21.467
Do they have any
legal right to be there?

37:21.539 --> 37:23.598
Technically... no.

37:23.674 --> 37:26.142
Then get rid of them.

37:26.210 --> 37:28.075
Thank you.

37:28.145 --> 37:31.603
<i>This house is the last thing
in our way.</i>

37:39.490 --> 37:42.084
[Woman and girl crying]

37:48.733 --> 37:50.667
I'll tell you, you ain't
gonna take our home.

37:50.735 --> 37:52.259
I don't care
what the paper says.

37:52.336 --> 37:54.065
Woman: No! No!

37:54.138 --> 37:56.265
- Get outta here!
- I'm out!

37:56.340 --> 37:58.240
Get out of here now!

37:59.677 --> 38:02.237
Now, why don't you give me
some more of your excuses

38:02.313 --> 38:05.043
as to why you don't have
that lease for Kamp Kikakee?!

38:07.251 --> 38:08.878
[Door closes,
engine turns over]

38:08.953 --> 38:10.147
[Crying continues]

38:10.221 --> 38:14.021
Boy, the guys
are gonna love this.

38:14.091 --> 38:16.457
Am I a genius or what?

38:16.527 --> 38:18.461
[Metal clanking]

38:18.529 --> 38:20.520
[Fire crackling]

38:25.836 --> 38:31.297
[Engine turns over, rumbles]

38:34.211 --> 38:36.145
[Squeaking]

38:48.893 --> 38:52.989
[Whistling melodically]

38:53.064 --> 38:54.725
[Engine stops]

38:56.167 --> 38:57.930
[Engine starts]

38:58.002 --> 39:01.165
Heh heh heh heh heh.

39:01.238 --> 39:03.399
[Squeaking]

39:04.942 --> 39:07.240
[Creaking]

39:14.385 --> 39:15.374
Oh! Oh!

39:15.453 --> 39:18.513
<i>Oh! Oh, oh! Oh!</i>

39:18.589 --> 39:21.023
Ohh! No, no, No-o-o-o!

39:21.092 --> 39:23.390
<i>Oh! Oh!</i>

39:23.461 --> 39:25.895
<i>Oh!</i>

39:25.963 --> 39:28.261
Aaah! Aaah!

39:28.332 --> 39:30.459
[Engine stops]

39:30.534 --> 39:32.968
Ah heh heh heh
heh heh heh.

39:33.037 --> 39:34.026
[Engine starts]

39:34.105 --> 39:36.605
Aaaaah!

39:36.674 --> 39:37.971
Aah! Aah!

39:38.042 --> 39:39.202
Aah! Aah! Aah! Aah!

39:39.276 --> 39:40.573
Ow! Ooh!

39:40.644 --> 39:42.908
[Air hisses]

39:42.980 --> 39:44.914
Ahhh. Ahhh.

39:44.982 --> 39:46.074
Uh!

39:46.150 --> 39:47.879
[Mud sloshing]

39:47.952 --> 39:51.319
Uh! Uh-uh-uh!

39:52.523 --> 39:54.115
[Indistinct conversations]

40:00.631 --> 40:02.724
[Boy laughs]

40:08.239 --> 40:09.763
<i>Men...</i>

40:09.840 --> 40:12.536
Before we begin
today's activities,

40:12.610 --> 40:14.100
I want to remind you

40:14.178 --> 40:17.170
that as a part of the path
of the brave,

40:17.248 --> 40:19.409
each cabin will have a project.

40:19.483 --> 40:21.417
That project should reflect

40:21.485 --> 40:24.249
the proud tradition
of Kamp Kikakee.

40:24.321 --> 40:27.347
- Wow. -
Wow. - Wow.

40:27.425 --> 40:30.121
The winner of last year's
competition

40:30.194 --> 40:33.095
made a full Indian
ceremonial headdress.

40:33.164 --> 40:35.655
<i>- So what? - So
what? - So what?</i>

40:35.733 --> 40:37.132
<i>This year...</i>

40:37.201 --> 40:40.659
I hope that one of our group
will do even better.

40:40.738 --> 40:42.797
Okay, fellas, let's get to it!

40:42.873 --> 40:44.807
[Cheers and applause]

40:44.875 --> 40:47.207
[Indistinct conversations]

40:49.747 --> 40:52.910
Okay, men, I want you to give
some special thought

40:52.983 --> 40:55.747
to the competition
Mr. Tipton talked about.

40:55.820 --> 40:59.278
Who knows? We might even
beat 'em at their own game.

40:59.356 --> 41:01.153
Yeah, with a little teamwork,

41:01.225 --> 41:03.819
with a little blood
and sweat and tears,

41:03.894 --> 41:05.691
we might just win.

41:05.763 --> 41:08.994
<i>Oh, come on, even a flounder
takes sides.</i>

41:09.066 --> 41:12.502
<i>Anybody got any ideas?</i>

41:12.570 --> 41:15.130
We could quit 'cause
we don't have a chance.

41:15.206 --> 41:16.605
Quit?

41:16.674 --> 41:19.074
Well, you know they ain't
gonna let us win anything.

41:19.143 --> 41:20.838
They don't even
want us to be here.

41:20.911 --> 41:23.379
<i>Man: Let's move out!
Everybody to the archery range!</i>

41:23.447 --> 41:25.347
Come on, fellas,
we got to at least try.

41:25.416 --> 41:27.748
I know! We could build
an authentic Indian tepee.

41:27.818 --> 41:29.718
You know, we could cut
some tall poles,

41:29.787 --> 41:33.120
and we could get some paint
and some special lashings and...

41:33.190 --> 41:34.953
[Sighs]

41:35.025 --> 41:38.517
Ernest, if you really want to
build a tepee, I'll help you.

41:38.596 --> 41:41.064
<i>Move it, short stuff!
We're waiting!</i>

41:43.133 --> 41:45.465
[Bird caws]

41:45.536 --> 41:49.870
21 degrees northwest
by 7 degrees southeast...

41:49.940 --> 41:52.135
divided by 6,
carry the one.

41:52.209 --> 41:54.643
<i>Miss St. Cloud:
Oh, hi, Ernest.</i>

41:54.712 --> 41:56.339
Oh, hi, Nurse St. Cloud.

41:56.413 --> 41:57.744
<i>Are you lost again?</i>

41:57.815 --> 42:00.477
Oh, no, no, no.
The woods are my home.

42:00.551 --> 42:02.781
Yes, I have
a working knowledge

42:02.853 --> 42:05.287
of every square inch
of this camp.

42:05.356 --> 42:06.948
I am at one with nature.

42:07.024 --> 42:09.083
Yeah, it's all
right here...

42:09.159 --> 42:11.059
<i>a keen sense of direction</i>

42:11.128 --> 42:14.859
and a firm grasp on the throttle
that controls the elements.

42:14.932 --> 42:17.400
Here. Have something
to eat.

42:17.468 --> 42:18.765
Thank you. Ahh!

42:18.836 --> 42:21.464
Peanut butter
on white bread...

42:21.539 --> 42:24.235
my favorite
rustic outdoor food.

42:24.308 --> 42:25.570
[Bird caws]

42:25.643 --> 42:29.135
Ah, this is the life...
the great outdoors,

42:29.213 --> 42:32.114
a beautiful woman,
plenty of food,

42:32.182 --> 42:34.116
and fire ants.

42:34.184 --> 42:36.414
Fire ants?!

42:36.487 --> 42:38.682
Ahhh!

42:38.756 --> 42:40.485
Owwww!

42:40.558 --> 42:43.550
<i>Ow! Ow!
Ow! Ow! Ow!</i>

42:43.627 --> 42:45.026
[Laughter]

42:45.095 --> 42:47.723
Shh! Whatever you do,
keep a straight face.

42:47.798 --> 42:50.130
Ernest, the boys
are here to see you.

42:50.200 --> 42:52.600
<i>Hey, Ernest!
You okay?</i>

42:52.670 --> 42:55.195
We heard about
the army of fire ants.

42:55.272 --> 42:58.332
Yeah, we brought you
a cheer-up present. Here.

42:58.409 --> 43:00.274
Ah! Thanks, fellas.

43:00.344 --> 43:03.142
You know, whatever they may say
about you, I'm gonna say, "Hey,

43:03.213 --> 43:05.579
"you're talking about
my guys," know what I mean?

43:05.649 --> 43:08.584
Go ahead, smell them,
Ernest. They're good.

43:08.652 --> 43:09.983
Mmm.

43:10.054 --> 43:14.491
<i>Notice
their aromatic bouquet.</i>

43:14.558 --> 43:16.150
[Sniffing]

43:17.895 --> 43:19.385
This is swell.

43:19.463 --> 43:21.488
This is the best get-well present
I ever had, know what I mean?

43:21.565 --> 43:23.294
Well, we'll see you,
Ernest.

43:23.367 --> 43:25.267
Yeah, man,
we'll be seeing you.

43:25.336 --> 43:26.928
- Catch you later.
- Bouquet!

43:27.004 --> 43:28.198
Well, thanks, fellas.

43:28.272 --> 43:30.001
Oh, man!

43:30.074 --> 43:31.473
[Laughter]

43:31.542 --> 43:34.602
Those kids are really great,
aren't they?

43:34.678 --> 43:36.976
That's what
they brought you?!

43:37.047 --> 43:39.277
It's a get-well present
from the boys.

43:39.350 --> 43:41.648
That's poison ivy, Ernest,

43:41.719 --> 43:44.552
<i>and with that much
coverage,</i>

43:44.622 --> 43:46.681
you're gonna need
another shot.

43:46.757 --> 43:49.726
Not again!

43:49.793 --> 43:51.727
Gosh!

43:51.795 --> 43:53.729
He was hugging it
and everything.

43:53.797 --> 43:56.095
He said it was his best
get-well present.

43:56.166 --> 43:57.565
<i>Boys...</i>

43:57.635 --> 44:00.604
I'm really disappointed
in you.

44:00.671 --> 44:02.662
That wasn't very nice.

44:02.740 --> 44:04.469
I was just a joke.

44:04.541 --> 44:07.271
Yeah, besides,
he's a jerk.

44:07.344 --> 44:10.370
Y-Yeah, well, we didn't mean
to do anything or...

44:10.447 --> 44:13.007
<i>Crutchfield: Yeah, we
didn't mean nothing by it.</i>

44:13.083 --> 44:17.486
Okay, okay,
you're right.

44:26.830 --> 44:30.960
It seems like the harder I try,
the worse things get.

44:33.437 --> 44:37.305
I like the boys, but I don't
think they like me.

44:39.777 --> 44:42.644
Mr. Tipton's
chewed me out twice.

44:42.713 --> 44:46.581
I guess I had it coming,
but it's still no fun,

44:46.650 --> 44:48.914
know what I mean?

44:48.986 --> 44:52.888
This counselor business
is harder than I thought,

44:52.956 --> 44:55.083
but it's what I want to do.

44:55.159 --> 44:59.926
Come on, Pokey, I need
to talk to somebody.

44:59.997 --> 45:02.795
I know you're dormant
and coldblooded

45:02.866 --> 45:04.299
and all that, but...

45:04.368 --> 45:07.134
Ow!

45:07.204 --> 45:08.535
Ow! Pokey!

45:08.605 --> 45:11.199
Ow! You heartless beast!

45:11.275 --> 45:13.539
Ow! Ow! [Panting]

45:13.610 --> 45:15.202
Pokey, Pokey, my sinuses!

45:15.279 --> 45:18.271
Pokey! Oh! You said
you'd never do this again!

45:18.348 --> 45:21.476
Ow! Ow!

45:21.552 --> 45:23.486
[Door squeaks]

45:23.554 --> 45:26.387
Heh heh heh
heh heh heh.

45:26.457 --> 45:28.220
Hey, Ernest!

45:28.292 --> 45:31.420
You got a turtle
on your nose, man!

45:31.495 --> 45:33.053
Oh, no, no, i-it's a zit.

45:33.130 --> 45:35.792
It comes back
every now and then. Heh heh.

45:35.866 --> 45:39.097
Hey, come on, fellas, we can jerk
that sucker off there in just a second.

45:39.169 --> 45:40.500
No! No, no!

45:40.571 --> 45:43.438
The only way to get him off
is to sing him to sleep!

45:43.507 --> 45:45.907
Okay, guys, come on.
Okay.

45:45.976 --> 45:48.843
A-one, A-two,
A-one, two, three.

45:48.912 --> 45:52.006
<i># Remember me and you
and you and me #</i>

45:52.082 --> 45:56.018
<i># No matter how they toss
the dice, it had to be #</i>

45:56.086 --> 45:59.647
<i># The only one for me is you
and you for me #</i>

45:59.723 --> 46:02.419
<i># So happy together #</i>

46:02.493 --> 46:06.020
<i># So, how is
the weather? #</i>

46:06.096 --> 46:08.428
[Engine rumbling]

46:08.499 --> 46:10.899
[Birds chirping]

46:23.714 --> 46:26.444
[Saw scraping,
sandpaper scratching]

46:26.517 --> 46:28.985
<i>Boy: What's going on?</i>

46:33.223 --> 46:34.554
[Hammer pounding]

46:34.625 --> 46:38.220
Well, look who's here.
It's the last-chance boys.

46:38.295 --> 46:39.523
How you doin', guys?

46:39.596 --> 46:41.826
They let you guys
run around loose?

46:41.899 --> 46:43.526
What are you makin'?

46:43.600 --> 46:46.694
It looks like a skeleton
or something.

46:46.770 --> 46:48.135
It's a kayak, airhead,

46:48.205 --> 46:50.696
and this baby's gonna win
the competition

46:50.774 --> 46:52.708
again for us
this year, pal.

46:55.579 --> 46:57.069
What are you guys
making?

46:57.147 --> 46:58.512
None of your business.

46:58.582 --> 47:00.140
Oh, a secret
project, huh?

47:00.217 --> 47:02.048
I wonder
what that could be.

47:02.119 --> 47:04.087
I bet they don't have
anything.

47:04.154 --> 47:06.418
- We do too!
- Oh, sure you do.

47:06.490 --> 47:10.256
Hey, you don't know nothing about nothing,
blondie, and I know that for a fact.

47:10.327 --> 47:11.919
Yeah, you'll see it
soon enough!

47:11.995 --> 47:13.986
- Yeah, when we win.
- Ooh, I'm real scared.

47:14.064 --> 47:16.555
That's it, man. Come on,
push me, punk! Come on!

47:16.633 --> 47:18.225
I'll have you
singing soprano!

47:18.302 --> 47:19.667
- Shut up!
- Come on, Vargas.

47:19.736 --> 47:21.328
- Don't tempt me.
- Come on, man.

47:23.807 --> 47:25.172
They don't have anything.

47:25.242 --> 47:26.937
Boy, what a bunch
of losers.

47:27.010 --> 47:28.773
[Scoffs]

47:28.846 --> 47:31.747
<i>- Okay, guys, come on!
- # You got me climbin' #</i>

47:31.815 --> 47:33.407
<i># Up from the bottom #</i>

47:33.483 --> 47:36.884
<i># You got me thinkin'
that we just can't lose #</i>

47:36.954 --> 47:38.717
<i># By pullin' together #</i>

47:38.789 --> 47:40.552
<i># We're gettin' stronger #</i>

47:40.624 --> 47:43.855
<i># We got a second chance,
and we'll break through #</i>

47:43.927 --> 47:46.418
<i># 'Cause when you're fightin'
for your life #</i>

47:46.496 --> 47:49.124
<i># You hold on tight #</i>

47:49.199 --> 47:51.633
<i># Don't let go
till you see the light #</i>

47:51.702 --> 47:54.227
<i># Can't stop
till the race is run #</i>

47:54.304 --> 47:56.204
<i>- Yeah! - All right! - #
We're gonna win this one #</i>

47:56.273 --> 47:58.571
- Whoo-hoo!
- Yeah!

47:58.642 --> 48:00.576
You know, Moose,

48:00.644 --> 48:04.239
recreating your genuine
Indian artifact

48:04.314 --> 48:08.307
is not just another
handicraft. It is a art.

48:08.385 --> 48:10.979
- Ernest?
- Mm-hmm?

48:11.054 --> 48:13.750
Do you think
if we win this contest,

48:13.824 --> 48:15.655
we could stay here forever

48:15.726 --> 48:19.059
and not have to go back
to that old institute?

48:19.129 --> 48:20.391
[Sighs]

48:20.464 --> 48:22.523
Well, if it was
up to me, Moose,

48:22.599 --> 48:24.794
you'd stay right here
from now on.

48:24.868 --> 48:27.393
Is it up to you?

48:27.471 --> 48:29.200
No.

48:29.273 --> 48:32.003
I didn't think so.

48:32.075 --> 48:34.009
[Gunshot]

48:37.147 --> 48:40.014
[Gunshot]

48:40.083 --> 48:41.607
[Shell clinks]

48:43.620 --> 48:46.214
Well, it's no use talking
to the old Indian.

48:46.290 --> 48:47.882
[Gunshot]

48:49.960 --> 48:51.621
[Shell clinks]

48:51.695 --> 48:54.129
I mean, the old guy
can't stop talking

48:54.197 --> 48:55.494
about the old ways...

48:55.565 --> 48:57.897
spirits, this kind of
voodoo mumbo jumbo.

48:57.968 --> 48:59.128
[Gunshot]

49:01.004 --> 49:03.097
Sherman,
you don't understand.

49:03.173 --> 49:05.698
The old guy will not
listen to reason.

49:05.776 --> 49:07.004
[Shell clinks]

49:07.077 --> 49:09.204
I mean,
who can own a tree?

49:09.279 --> 49:13.010
[Laughing] What?

49:13.083 --> 49:15.176
Nothing.

49:15.252 --> 49:17.584
You just haven't tried
hard enough.

49:17.654 --> 49:19.019
Money talks!

49:19.089 --> 49:21.683
Sherman, we could be
on very shaky ground here.

49:21.758 --> 49:23.225
There's the old treaty...

49:23.293 --> 49:26.023
This is the real world!
We're playing hardball!

49:26.096 --> 49:28.155
You just can't be
soft and polite

49:28.231 --> 49:30.392
and expect things
to come your way!

49:30.467 --> 49:34.528
I got too much
riding on this...

49:34.604 --> 49:37.004
and I'm not gonna let
some old Indian

49:37.074 --> 49:39.133
throw a monkey wrench
into it.

49:44.948 --> 49:46.643
[Gunshot]

49:46.717 --> 49:49.686
<i>Hey, hand me that string
over there, will you?</i>

49:49.753 --> 49:51.220
<i>Okay.</i>

49:51.288 --> 49:54.018
<i>Yeah, the inside's really
starting to look nice.</i>

49:54.091 --> 49:58.027
These boys have really jumped into
this competition with both feet.

49:58.095 --> 50:00.495
They just needed something
to be proud of.

50:02.766 --> 50:05.826
Hey, Crutch, next time
I run away from the institute,

50:05.902 --> 50:08.427
I'm gonna build myself
one of these things.

50:08.505 --> 50:10.097
Hey, dudes,
check it out.

50:10.173 --> 50:11.800
Now, that's
no slouch job.

50:11.875 --> 50:14.605
Hey, you know, we just
might win this thing.

50:14.678 --> 50:16.908
You know, I think
I might have a knack

50:16.980 --> 50:18.447
for this
construction biz.

50:18.515 --> 50:19.607
[Knife clinking]

50:19.683 --> 50:21.617
[Birds chirping]

50:21.685 --> 50:23.550
<i>Somebody
give me a hand.</i>

50:23.620 --> 50:25.417
<i>Hey,
I'll help you out.</i>

50:25.489 --> 50:28.151
And then he thought
he heard it,

50:28.225 --> 50:31.126
and that's when Vernon
turned around

50:31.194 --> 50:33.719
and looked in his rear window,

50:33.797 --> 50:36.664
and there,
staring back at him,

50:36.733 --> 50:38.291
was the Hook Man!

50:38.368 --> 50:41.462
Ah ha ha ha ha ha
ha ha ha ha!

50:41.538 --> 50:44.666
So, he stomped on the gas,
and he tore outta there!

50:44.741 --> 50:47.676
<i>And the next day, Vernon
went out to get in his car,</i>

50:47.744 --> 50:51.271
and there, hanging
on the rearview mirror,

50:51.348 --> 50:52.872
was the hook!

50:52.949 --> 50:55.213
I thought it was supposed
to be on the door handle.

50:55.285 --> 50:56.217
<i>- Ha ha.
- Yeah.</i>

50:56.286 --> 50:57.548
Yeah, it was originally,

50:57.621 --> 51:00.419
but, uh, but then Vernon hung it
on the rearview mirror,

51:00.490 --> 51:03.118
you know, like a souvenir,
like dice and baby shoes.

51:03.193 --> 51:05.559
Uh-huh.

51:05.629 --> 51:09.656
Ah heh. Well, does anybody else,
uh, have an interesting story?

51:09.733 --> 51:13.225
Uh, chief, uh, can you
tell us a big story?

51:13.303 --> 51:17.000
Heh heh heh.

51:17.074 --> 51:21.272
[Speaking native language]

51:23.513 --> 51:25.640
I speak
to the young braves

51:25.715 --> 51:28.912
so that they may know
of the old ways.

51:28.985 --> 51:31.920
[Speaking native language]

51:31.988 --> 51:35.219
<i>I speak to them
so that they may know</i>

51:35.292 --> 51:39.388
<i>what this ground holds
of the spirits of the past.</i>

51:39.463 --> 51:41.863
<i>[Speaking native language]</i>

51:46.002 --> 51:49.870
When a young brave was ready
to become a warrior,

51:49.940 --> 51:51.840
<i>it was here
that he was called</i>

51:51.908 --> 51:53.773
<i>by the wise men
and the elders.</i>

51:53.844 --> 51:56.278
<i>[Speaking native language]</i>

51:56.346 --> 51:59.213
<i>If he had faith
in the great one,</i>

51:59.282 --> 52:01.807
<i>the knife
would not cut him.</i>

52:01.885 --> 52:04.353
<i>[Speaking native language]</i>

52:04.421 --> 52:07.288
<i>If he had courage,
true courage,</i>

52:07.357 --> 52:10.793
<i>the rock
would not break him.</i>

52:10.861 --> 52:14.661
<i>[Speaking native language]</i>

52:14.731 --> 52:17.393
<i>If the brave
was pure of heart,</i>

52:17.467 --> 52:19.867
<i>the arrow
could not catch him.</i>

52:19.936 --> 52:22.700
<i>[Speaking native language]</i>

52:22.772 --> 52:26.105
<i>And then he would become
a warrior,</i>

52:26.176 --> 52:28.041
<i>as someday you will.</i>

52:28.111 --> 52:29.669
<i>[Speaking native language]</i>

52:32.883 --> 52:34.214
And that was called

52:34.284 --> 52:37.447
the ceremony of the blade,
the stone, and the arrow.

52:37.521 --> 52:41.082
Like in our culture...
paper, rock, scissors.

52:44.127 --> 52:45.685
[All groan]

52:45.762 --> 52:48.230
[Bird calling in distance]

52:48.298 --> 52:50.061
[Laughter]

52:50.133 --> 52:52.465
Man, that sure was some rap
the old chief was putting on us.

52:52.536 --> 52:54.265
Yeah, I wonder
if that stuff is true.

52:54.337 --> 52:56.305
Well, you wouldn't catch me
standing around

52:56.373 --> 52:58.204
letting some lunatic
throw knives at me.

52:58.275 --> 52:59.333
Whap!

52:59.409 --> 53:01.138
[Fire igniting]

53:01.211 --> 53:03.873
Oh, no!
That's our tepee!

53:08.485 --> 53:11.352
Who did this?

53:14.691 --> 53:18.127
Who do you think?

53:18.195 --> 53:20.288
Man, let's get 'em!

53:20.363 --> 53:22.422
Yeah, come on!

53:26.436 --> 53:28.961
Looks like you fellas
forgot something here.

53:29.039 --> 53:31.735
[Sniffs] We wouldn't
want you to get thirsty,

53:31.808 --> 53:34.402
<i>now, would we, fellas?</i>

53:34.477 --> 53:37.969
So we come to repay
the favor.

53:38.048 --> 53:40.812
[Indistinct shouting,
fighting]

53:40.884 --> 53:43.216
<i>Mr. Tipton: Your boys
are out of control.</i>

53:43.286 --> 53:45.914
<i>I mean, this last fight,
it was the last straw.</i>

53:45.989 --> 53:48.457
I've got other campers
I've got to think about here.

53:48.525 --> 53:50.288
I think it's best
for all concerned

53:50.360 --> 53:52.692
if we just send them all
back to the institution,

53:52.762 --> 53:54.889
where they can get
the supervision they need.

53:54.998 --> 53:56.488
Don't do it, sir.

53:56.566 --> 53:59.763
<i>Ernest, it's not really
your fault. It's my fault.</i>

53:59.836 --> 54:02.805
I thought you could do it.
I was wrong.

54:02.872 --> 54:04.897
But it's not fair
to send them back.

54:04.975 --> 54:07.671
It's not their fault.
Maybe I was a bad counselor.

54:07.744 --> 54:09.939
They shouldn't have to
suffer for that.

54:10.013 --> 54:14.279
<i>Look, if you give the
second-chance boys another chance</i>

54:14.351 --> 54:17.343
and me another chance,
that'll be three chances,

54:17.420 --> 54:20.878
and added to the two chances
we had before, that makes...

54:20.957 --> 54:23.482
five or six chances...
carry the one...

54:23.560 --> 54:25.687
<i>Okay, Ernest,
one more chance.</i>

54:25.762 --> 54:27.423
I'll let the boys stay,

54:27.497 --> 54:30.364
but they better
get with the program...

54:30.433 --> 54:31.957
you know what I mean?

54:32.035 --> 54:34.765
Oh, I know what you mean.
Yes, sir. Thank you.

54:34.838 --> 54:37.466
[Speaking Japanese]
Thank you.

54:38.375 --> 54:39.569
They were all set

54:39.643 --> 54:42.305
to send you boys
back to the institute,

54:42.379 --> 54:45.507
when you-know-who stepped in
and saved the day.

54:45.582 --> 54:48.176
See? I told you
he wasn't such a dork.

54:48.251 --> 54:50.242
But they burned it,
Ernest.

54:50.320 --> 54:52.311
One monkey
don't stop no show.

54:52.389 --> 54:54.289
We can still win
this thing.

54:54.357 --> 54:56.791
Aw, come on, Ernest,
what's the point?

54:56.860 --> 54:59.090
The point is
to do your best always,

54:59.162 --> 55:01.221
to always give it
your best shot,

55:01.298 --> 55:04.790
[Deep voice] To boldly go
where no man has gone before.

55:04.868 --> 55:07.302
[Normal voice]
It's the path of the brave.

55:07.370 --> 55:10.066
Well, I don't know
about you guys,

55:10.140 --> 55:13.132
<i>but I'm not gonna let 'em
put me down.</i>

55:13.209 --> 55:15.837
I'm gonna build
this thing over.

55:18.815 --> 55:21.249
<i>Hey, yeah, guys,
he's right.</i>

55:21.318 --> 55:22.751
Come on, let's go.

55:22.819 --> 55:26.255
Ernest,
it's a lead-pipe city.

55:26.323 --> 55:28.518
Yeah.

55:36.633 --> 55:38.760
[Vehicle approaches]

55:45.642 --> 55:49.373
[Brakes squeak, engine stops]

55:52.515 --> 55:55.609
[Car door closes]

55:57.821 --> 56:01.018
Mr. Wind Cloud...

56:01.091 --> 56:03.355
Ah, this looks like
a museum.

56:03.426 --> 56:06.691
Ha ha ha! I can feel
the history here.

56:06.763 --> 56:09.391
Mr. Wind Cloud,
I am Sherman Krader,

56:09.466 --> 56:11.297
Krader Mining Corporation.

56:11.368 --> 56:15.134
My attorney, Mr. Blatz, has
conveyed to you my very...

56:15.205 --> 56:17.469
[Birds chirping]

56:20.610 --> 56:23.078
My attorney, Mr. Blatz,

56:23.146 --> 56:25.944
has conveyed to you
my very generous offer

56:26.015 --> 56:29.109
to obtain a lease on
a portion of land that you,

56:29.185 --> 56:32.416
as one of the last members
of your tribe, control.

56:32.489 --> 56:35.287
I'll... and I'm here
to double that offer.

56:35.358 --> 56:37.485
I know it's not
very fair to me,

56:37.560 --> 56:39.687
but, um, I realize
there's a lot

56:39.763 --> 56:41.856
of sentimental
attachment here,

56:41.931 --> 56:44.024
and I'm prepared
to offer you

56:44.100 --> 56:46.500
a 10% royalty
on all the petrocite

56:46.569 --> 56:50.300
that we can mine out of
the Kikakee area... 10%!

56:53.042 --> 56:54.805
Mr. Wind Cloud...

56:54.878 --> 56:58.541
Mr. Wind Cloud,
I don't think you understand.

56:58.615 --> 57:02.107
Now, you'd be a fool
not to sign this paper.

57:02.185 --> 57:05.018
Mr. Wind Cloud,
you have to sign this paper!

57:05.088 --> 57:06.646
It's your patriotic duty!

57:06.723 --> 57:07.781
[Pen clicks]

57:10.593 --> 57:13.357
Do you understand
a word I've been saying?

57:15.231 --> 57:17.358
Uh, chief...

57:17.434 --> 57:19.959
your canoe
is in the river.

57:20.036 --> 57:21.697
Oh, I'm sorry.

57:21.771 --> 57:24.137
I didn't know
you had company.

57:24.207 --> 57:27.074
[Speaking
native language]

57:29.648 --> 57:32.242
Excuse me.

57:32.317 --> 57:35.115
I'm, uh, Bob Wilson...
maybe you could help me...

57:35.187 --> 57:37.951
Department of, uh, Soils
and Water Conservation.

57:38.023 --> 57:40.651
Um, I'm having a little
problem communicating

57:40.726 --> 57:42.591
with, uh,
Mr. Wind Cloud here.

57:42.661 --> 57:45.653
You see, there's a... there's,
um, a strip-mining company

57:45.731 --> 57:47.528
on the upper part
of the river.

57:47.599 --> 57:49.590
I'm getting
all the landowners here

57:49.668 --> 57:52.193
to sign this petition
to stop their activities

57:52.271 --> 57:54.398
before they completely
ruin the river.

57:54.473 --> 57:57.840
Now, maybe you can
[Laughs] "talk" to him.

57:57.910 --> 57:58.934
Ha ha ha.

57:59.011 --> 58:00.945
And get him
to sign this.

58:01.013 --> 58:04.073
Communicating with your
Native-American cultures

58:04.149 --> 58:05.616
is a specialty of mine.

58:05.684 --> 58:06.708
I'm bilingual.

58:06.785 --> 58:08.343
It's a difficult skill,

58:08.420 --> 58:11.514
but one which I acquired
after years of study.

58:11.590 --> 58:14.024
Mister, you have come
to the right man.

58:14.092 --> 58:18.256
<i>No problemo.
Comprendo, dÃ©jÃ  vu?</i>

58:18.330 --> 58:20.628
Yes, I do. Yeah.
Thank you.

58:20.699 --> 58:24.226
[Speaks
native language]

58:36.982 --> 58:40.418
This is a sad day
for Kamp Kikakee.

58:40.485 --> 58:42.919
I've got here a signed order

58:42.988 --> 58:46.151
that says
the camp's got to close.

58:46.225 --> 58:47.988
Oh, man.

58:48.060 --> 58:49.755
What?

58:49.828 --> 58:50.920
I'm sorry, fellas.

58:50.996 --> 58:53.191
We're gonna have to pack
and leave.

58:53.265 --> 58:54.232
What's happened?

58:54.299 --> 58:56.062
This doesn't make
any sense.

58:56.134 --> 59:00.070
The chief has signed away
control of the land

59:00.138 --> 59:02.265
to Krader Mining Company.

59:02.341 --> 59:07.301
<i>[Sighs] Krader takes over
the day after tomorrow.</i>

59:07.379 --> 59:09.904
They're gonna move in
their heavy equipment,

59:09.982 --> 59:12.883
and they are going to destroy
everything around here

59:12.951 --> 59:14.885
<i>looking for some mineral.</i>

59:17.522 --> 59:20.150
<i>I'm sorry, guys.</i>

59:20.225 --> 59:22.386
<i>I'm sorry this happened.</i>

59:24.496 --> 59:28.956
Somebody had to...
[Sighs]

59:29.034 --> 59:32.731
...fast-talk the chief
into signing.

59:32.804 --> 59:35.329
Ohhh.

59:35.407 --> 59:37.967
Uh. [Sighs]

59:38.043 --> 59:43.447
Okay, guys, let's get packed up.
We got to get out of here.

59:43.515 --> 59:45.039
There are only
two people here

59:45.117 --> 59:46.914
who can communicate
with grandfather.

59:46.985 --> 59:48.919
L-It's all a great big
misunderstanding.

59:48.987 --> 59:50.614
I'll fix it up,
know what I mean?

59:50.689 --> 59:52.850
I'll fix it.
You'll see.

01:00:02.234 --> 01:00:03.360
[Brakes squeak]

01:00:18.116 --> 01:00:20.482
Man, this is such
a major bummer.

01:00:20.552 --> 01:00:21.985
What are we gonna do?

01:00:22.054 --> 01:00:24.614
Go back to the institution. What else?

01:00:24.690 --> 01:00:27.056
<i>I was gettin'
to like it here.</i>

01:00:27.125 --> 01:00:29.685
<i>Hey, I ain't goin' back
to no institution.</i>

01:00:29.761 --> 01:00:31.058
<i>- Me neither.
- No way.</i>

01:00:31.129 --> 01:00:34.587
Nobody's gonna have to
go anywhere.

01:00:34.666 --> 01:00:38.500
I knew you'd think
of something, Ernest.

01:00:38.570 --> 01:00:40.663
You've got a plan?

01:00:40.739 --> 01:00:44.835
Yep. I'm gonna settle this
lease thing once and for all.

01:00:44.910 --> 01:00:47.174
Yeah,
settle it, Ernest.

01:00:47.245 --> 01:00:48.576
Yeah,
this I want to see.

01:00:48.647 --> 01:00:51.013
Course, I might have to
jack a few jaws,

01:00:51.083 --> 01:00:53.051
pass out a couple
of knuckle sandwiches.

01:00:53.118 --> 01:00:55.313
<i>All right!
Now you're talking!</i>

01:00:55.387 --> 01:00:57.514
- Come on, fellas. Let's watch the man work.
- Yeah.

01:00:57.589 --> 01:00:59.523
[Bed squeaks]

01:00:59.591 --> 01:01:01.821
See these hands, huh?
Huh? Huh? You see 'em?

01:01:01.893 --> 01:01:03.724
If I put these hands
in my pockets,

01:01:03.795 --> 01:01:06.559
I will be arrested for carrying
concealed deadly weapons,

01:01:06.631 --> 01:01:08.496
know what I mean?

01:01:08.567 --> 01:01:09.898
- Whoa! -
Whoa! - Whoa!

01:01:09.968 --> 01:01:11.265
- Yeah!
- Yeah!

01:01:11.336 --> 01:01:13.634
Go! Whoo!

01:01:14.806 --> 01:01:17.468
[Jackhammer pounds]

01:01:24.616 --> 01:01:27.380
[Brakes squeak]

01:01:27.452 --> 01:01:29.886
I want to talk to the punk

01:01:29.955 --> 01:01:32.753
<i>who is responsible for
the actions of this company.</i>

01:01:32.824 --> 01:01:34.121
Now!

01:01:40.532 --> 01:01:42.432
Ah heh. Ohhh.

01:01:44.836 --> 01:01:47.600
Ah heh heh heh heh.

01:01:47.672 --> 01:01:50.232
<i>Ohh.</i>

01:01:50.308 --> 01:01:52.435
Ah heh heh heh heh
heh heh heh.

01:01:52.511 --> 01:01:54.445
<i>Come on, Ernest.</i>

01:01:54.513 --> 01:01:55.741
Destroy
the evil vigilance!

01:01:55.814 --> 01:01:57.008
Come on, Ernest!

01:01:57.082 --> 01:01:59.778
You got him! You got him!
He's not that big.

01:01:59.851 --> 01:02:02.115
<i>Jack his jaw, Ernest.</i>

01:02:02.187 --> 01:02:03.586
Yeah!
Turn out his lights!

01:02:03.655 --> 01:02:04.986
Oh, I don't know.

01:02:05.056 --> 01:02:07.456
I-I think his jaw
looks pretty well jacked.

01:02:07.526 --> 01:02:09.824
Real nice.
Ah heh heh heh heh.

01:02:09.895 --> 01:02:12.489
Nice hat, too.
Heh heh heh heh.

01:02:12.564 --> 01:02:13.588
Uhh!

01:02:13.665 --> 01:02:14.689
Come on, Ernest!
Get up!

01:02:14.766 --> 01:02:15.664
- Come on! Come on!
- Let's go, man!

01:02:15.734 --> 01:02:17.326
[Men cheering]

